The resulting `greeting` variable is set to the concatenated string "Hello World." This is useful when you want to join multiple pieces of text together or create custom messages.

Literals are direct values that can be assigned to variables, used in expressions, or passed as arguments to procedures. In OpenROAD, literals can take various forms such as numbers, strings, and Boolean values (true/false). Here's an example of using literals in an expression:
```scss
num1 = 42;
str1 = "Hello World!";
boolean_value = true;
...
if (num1 > 0) then
    display "Number is positive.";
end if;
if (str1 == "Hello World!") then
    display "The string is correct.";
end if;
if (boolean_value) then
    display "Boolean value is true.";
else
    display "Boolean value is false.";
end if;
```
In this example, literals are used in various ways throughout the code. `42`, `"Hello World!"`, and `true` are examples of literals. They are assigned to variables (`num1`, `str1`, `boolean_value`) and also used directly in expressions and conditions.

OpenROAD supports various arithmetic operations including addition (`+`), subtraction (`-`), multiplication (`*`), division (`/`), and modulo (`%`). Arithmetic expressions can be used in assignments, within procedures, or as conditions for control structures. Here's an example of using arithmetic operations:
```css
x = 20;
y = 15;
sum = x + y;
product = x * y;
quotient = x / y;
remainder = x % y;
...
if (remainder == 0) then
    display "Number x is divisible by y.";
else
    display "Number x is not divisible by y.";
end if;
```
In this example, arithmetic expressions are used to perform basic operations on two variables, `x` and `y`. The resulting values (`sum`, `product`, `quotient`, and `remainder`) can be used in other expressions or assigned to variables. The modulo operation is also used to check whether `x` is divisible by `y`.
